    skipping the non-existent 3-octet length) and its dispatch,
    and POD (=head2 euctw catalog entry; Char-EUCTW moved into the legacy
    mapping table and removed from the "partially subsumed" note).  Like eucjp,
    euctw is a Unix encoding and is intentionally NOT added to the MSWin32
    trailing-\x5C DAMEMOJI groups even though the 4-octet final octet can be
    \x5C, because EUC-TW is not a Windows ANSI code page.  Stray high octets
    follow mb's strict model (non-characters), matching how eucjp treats them.
    New tests: t/1017_euctw_structure.t (4/2-octet length/substr/index/rindex/
    reverse/chop, the transpiled anchor, and SS2 four-octet hyphen-range cases
